"Pours a hazy dark brown, opaque in glass, thick dense tan foam, big chunks of lace down the glass. Smell: porter-y... medium roast coffee, note of oak smoke, milk chocolate, black plum. Minimal floral hop character. Taste: roasty and snappy + smoked grain, baking chocolate, mildly herbal and earthy, with a little tart stone fruit sweetness. There's a very mild acidic bite throughout. Light bodied with a relaxed but fluffy feel. Really quite interesting, tasty and refreshing."
""
"Gratzer starts with decent tan foam head that leaves good lacing in the glass. The liquid is an opaque black liquid that definitely matches the theme well. On the nose I smell sweet smoked barley with a hint of floral hops. The flavor is overpowered with so much smoke it is nearly undrinkable for me. The mouth feel is certainly excellent, but overall this beer is a bit too simple on the nose with way too much smoke on the tongue to be recommended. If you love the flavor of smoke you'll be in love otherwise steer clear. Both companies have better options."
"Pours a medium brown with white head, decent retention. The aroma starts with heavy smoked malt. Notes of campfire, burnt wood, and other things associated with smoke come to mind. Perhaps a bit overdone in the smoke department. Some roast comes through as well, no apparent lacto on the aroma. The taste starts with chocolate and smoke. Started like a smoke forward smoked porter, not too bad, nothing crazy. Then comes a *hint* of lactobacillus which just makes this beer weird. It doesn't really come across as being tart or sour, just that implied hint of sour wheat. This is followed by some lager yeast notes. Mouthfeel is light and well carbonated. I give this beer props for being unique, but it certainly lacks in the realm of balance. I think a heavier lacto profile and a bit less malt would have really made for an interesting beer."
