"nothing like i know gratzers to be. lightly smoked wheat based beers, usually fluffy and blonde. i guess it isnt written in the rules anywhere that it cant be dark wheat malt, and thats exactly whats going on in this three floyds joint effort. pours like a ported, dark dark brown, barley letting light pass, and sporting over an inch of tan milkshake textured head. the nose on it is only subtly smoky, not as intense as expected, but the malts are real roasty, and this again seems more like a robust porter than a gratzer as i know the style. the flavor also shows only a little smoke, its there all the way through, but it isnt the main flavor agent. the chewy dark grains are, and they crowd out the more delicate wheat and smoke properties i was looking for. surprised its not 10% abv, given the involvement of three floyds on this thing, the low abv makes it rather drinkable, despite being a confusing experience. tough to call this one a true gratzer i think, but i like it because it is something different. one of the better lips of faith releases in awhile, but dont expect anything conventional here."
